{
  "doc_id": "23652",
  "text": "The initial amplifier in visual transduction is a photoactivated state (R*) of a photopigment G-protein-coupled receptor (GPCR); in vertebrate rod photoreceptors, the GPCR is rhodopsin. Biochemical evidence has long supported the conclusion that inactivation of R* in vertebrate rod photoreceptors involves phosphorylation by the G-protein-coupled receptor kinase GRK1 (\"rhodopsin kinase\") of one or more serine residues on the rhodopsin C terminus [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
